  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For if I make you sorry.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The verse may be rendered. \"For if I pain you, who then is it that gladdens me except he who is being pained by me?\" The \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "I\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " being expressed in the original, is emphatic, and the verse has none of the strange selfish meaning which has been assigned to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", namely, that St. Paul thought \"the grief which he had caused to be amply compensated for by the pleasure he received from that grief.\" It has the much simpler meaning that he was unwilling to pain those who gladdened him, and therefore would not pay them a visit which could only be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "painful",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " on both sides, when the normal relation between them should be one of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "joy",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " on both sides, as he has already said (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 1:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The singular, \"he who is being pained by me",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",\" does not refer to the offender, but to the Corinthians collectively. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Who is he then,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " etc.? The \"then\" in the original is classically and elegantly expressed by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "καὶ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "James 2:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). 2 Corinthians 2:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "If I make, etc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "I is emphatic, implying that there are enough others who caused them trouble.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Who then is he, etc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The thought underlying the passage, 1:24-2:3, is that the apostle's own joy is bound up with the spiritual prosperity of the Church. Compare Philippians 4:1. As the helper of their joy he would receive joy through their faith and obedience. So long as their moral condition compelled him to come, bringing rebuke and pain, they could not be a source of joy to him. If I must needs make you sorry with merited rebuke, who can give me joy save you who are thus made sorry? ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The thought underlying the passage, 1:24-2:3, is that the apostle's own joy is bound up with the spiritual prosperity of the Church. Compare ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Philippians 4:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". As the helper of their joy he would receive joy through their faith and obedience. So long as their moral condition compelled him to come, bringing rebuke and pain, they could not be a source of joy to him. If I must needs make you sorry with merited rebuke, who can give me joy save you who are thus made sorry? ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
